messages.title: Health privacy threatened
messages.content: Camden Green Party is urging residents to think twice before they upload personal details onto the new national database.

keyPolicies.policyDescription: Plans for the building of new council homes at Maiden Lane estate are opposed due to the size of the proposed units, with a call for a greater quantity of affordable housing.
The party aims to tackle economic inequality through introducing minimum wage and maximum earnings, investing in public transport, house building, and green industries.

issues.economy: A minimum wage increase, maximum earnings, investment in public transport, house building, and green industries.
issues.health: Concerns over the national health database threatening patient privacy.
issues.socialWelfare: Introducing a minimum wage and maximum earnings to address economic inequality.

housing.content: Opposition to size of proposed units at Maiden Lane estate, advocating for more affordable housing.

contactInformation.address: Camden Green Party Freepost RSGU-GCUX-BLAX 56 Walker House, London NW1 1EP

images.caption: Leaflet images depicting Camden Green News header, housing, and a photo of Green Party campaigner Natalie Bennett.

leaflet.additionalNotes: The leaflet discusses concerns over health data privacy, housing issues, and economic inequality. It also includes a section on how to help and support the Camden Green Party.
